Corrected again in favor of below $1.30, reasons: Tightening race according to the polls, increased uncertainty will keep the exchange rate low until the election. At this stage, only a larger than expected Tory victory could be anticipated to boost the exchange rate as a reaction, but I see this as unlikely (<20% probability), and even in the case the Tories win by a larger than expected margin, I see no reason why it should rise above $1.30 when it did not trade at those levels when a large victory was anticipated from the polls.

The pound dropped on political risks - polls suddenly indicating a tightening race. However, there are reasons to believe this is a polling fluke (see https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-26/sterling-slips-as-poll-shows-tory-lead-narrows-after-bomb-attack, which also has a nice chart linking traders' expectations of the link between the election result and the pound). Nevertheless, unless the polls reverse quickly in favor of a large Tory victory, the pound is likely to remain below 1.30 until the election and then react to the election result. The pound has picked up a little against the dollar and euro. Some analysts give as a reason that they believe that the Brexit negotiations will produce a compromise between the UK and EU, but they might just be looking for any reason explain to the rise. Some have quoted: http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-eu-trade-britain-idUKKBN17T1HN A rational person might well take the view that a free trade deal will be agreed, after all its in the interest of both the EU and UK. However most economists would also say that it would have been in the interests of the UK to not have voted for Brexit, but the UK did vote for Brexit. Which I guess proves that decisions are not always rational. The longer it is before the UK arrives at a trade deal with the EU, the greater the risk of the UK hitting a downward Investment Spiral There is a considerable lag between good or bad news and its affect on business investment (probable about 18 months). If the bad news was the Brexit vote in June 2016, the effects on investment will arrive around the end of 2017, but the effects of the economy as a whole will only be starting in 2018. The lack of investment will be damaging to productivity, which will hit profits unless the pound falls. http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/brexit-business-investment-weak-2017-bank-of-england-credit-conditions-a7681686.html Even if a UK EU free trade deal is agreed it will probable not be before 2019, by then there will have been at least a year of low business investment and a successful free trade agreement in might not result in business investment actually taking place until 2020 and feeding through to the economy until 2021. That's quite a wait.

I am stating the obvious; the rate could change due to the dollar becoming more desirable or the pound becoming less desirable. The big factor that might affect the pound is the Brexit negotiations, but the market thinks it knows what is likely to happen with this between now and the end of June - the EU will presumably formally agree to the plan that Tusk has already outlined, talks on the status of citizens may have started by July but he does not expect anything to have been agreed and talks about things that would affect the value of the pound will not have started. It is more likely that something will happen that will affect the value of the dollar. It is considered likely that US interest rate may rise, which would tend to make the dollar more attractive, but the markets have probably already built that in to the dollar's current price (in fact the dollar might rise in anticipation and fall a little on it actually happening).

The simple fact is major trading currencies do not typically fluctuate in relative value very much over the short term. Volatility between the major currencies tends to be only a few cents or less either way in a normal day and even month. There was a sharp drop in the value of the pound after the Brexit referendum (see link) but since then the pound has stabilized between 1.2 and 1.3; that combined with the fact that starting the Brexit process should be priced in already means there would have to be a truly shocking shock to move the pound outside that band.
